label chapter6:

    # [Scene: Rooftop Terrace | Night — Storm Rolling In]

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Percussive drums, high strings—urgent]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Foghorn bellowing, wind tearing at canvas, distant glass popping]
    "You taste iron and salt on the wind before you hear the first, clean crack—the sound of something important giving way out on the water. For a breath you forget the lists, the meeting, Calder's clauses;"
    "there is only this immediate, vertical danger and the fact that the town is right beneath it."
    "Your hands go cold. Your Moleskine is gone from your neck; it slid free in the scramble and somewhere someone is shouting a name you can't catch. The terrace lights blur into streaks; the edge of"
    "the roof looks like it might fold into the sky. You want to run. You want to stand still. Both are the same kind of fear."
    "You hear Arin's voice—sharp, practical, and close enough to ground you."
    show arin_kai at left:
        zoom 0.7

    arin_kai "Maya! The pier's taking it. People are calling for help—boats are breaking loose."
    show maya_soler at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_soler "Where— (you taste the words like metal) —which side? Tell me."

    arin_kai "All of it. North spit, the Flats, down by the lantern house. The tide's a liar tonight."
    "You shouldn't be surprised. You have lived in Lira Bay long enough to know how quickly the sea will learn a new song and sing it loud. But knowing doesn't buffer the shock when the song"
    "becomes a wall. Your breath comes with ragged permission. You tie your jacket as wind tries to peel it away, and you run."
    # [Scene: Fisherman's Pier & Lantern House | Night — Storm Heightening]
    hide arin_kai
    hide maya_soler

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_2 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Chaotic percussion, a brass stab every few seconds]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Timber snapping, ropes screaming, the sea tinkling with broken glass]
    "The pier is a wire of people and shouts; hands try to catch loose ropes, arms flail for studs and cleats. You land on your knees, palms finding wet wood, smelling diesel and algae and something burnt. A volunteer pushes past you, face white and wet, mouth working without sound."
    show arin_kai at left:
        zoom 0.7

    arin_kai "We lost a cage. Two more downstream—hold that line, Maya, don't let it slip."
    show maya_soler at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_soler "I'm right— (you grab the rope; it bites into your palms) —I'm not letting go."
    "You throw your weight into the line. The rope slides under your gloves, slick and alive. The net comes up with a living, dying tangle—oysters split, mud crawled between them, young shoots of planted marsh torn"
    "free like ragged hair. A volunteer collapses onto the planks and the sound she makes is a single, animal thing."

    "Volunteer" "They were—three summers—gone—"
    "You want to make promises that will stitch the night back together. Instead you wrap an arm around the volunteer because the motion is something you can do and because you used to believe action could be a talisman against helplessness."

    menu:
        "Help Arin pull the net all the way aboard":
            "You plant your feet, synchronize your pulls with Arin's grunts. The net jerks; a cascade of mud and broken shells slams onto the pier. You both cough, hands numb with cold, and for a moment the two of you are a machine: effective and raw."
        "Run along the pilings to check the planted stakes in the flats":
            "You sprint, the wind lashing at your back. You wobble along the slick pilings to the marsh edge where stakes lean like drowned ghosts. Your fingers find one, the marker for a row of seedlings—it's snapped off clean, the soil around it scoured and hollow."

    # --- merge ---
    "The choice doesn't feel like one. Both things are true and both rip at you. You do what you can."
    # [Scene: The Flats (Tidal Marsh Restoration Site) | Night — Flood and Tears]
    hide arin_kai
    hide maya_soler

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_3 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: High-pitched sustained strings; heartbeat bass]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The slapping of water, people yelling over the wind, the low moan of something breaking]
    "You find the marsh a ruin in miniature. Where the seedlings had stood in tidy intervals there are ragged holes—earth gone as if scooped out by some enormous, indifferent hand. Oyster cages, the small experiments you"
    "slept worrying over, are like overturned toys on the tides. The data stakes you set with such careful fingers lean or are gone entirely."
    "A handful of volunteers cluster under a tarp, faces hollow. Lina stands there, water running down her beanie, eyes red. Rita is at the edge, her scarf gone wet and matted against her throat; she clutches"
    "an old map to her chest as if it were a talisman. You want to step forward and tell them what will mend this—an experimental planting, more funding, a policy change—but the words are paper-thin against"
    "the raw weather."
    "You hear Evelyn before you see her: boots clomping through pooling water, the sheen of a trench coat that looks absurdly neat in all this collapse. Trucks from the construction site crawl up the road behind"
    "her like slow, late rescue ships. They are armored, heavy, a promise that arrived at the wrong time."
    show evelyn_hart at left:
        zoom 0.7

    evelyn_hart "We moved as fast as policy and contractors allow. We—"
    show maya_soler at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_soler "You moved after the breach. The pumps—where did they put them? Who rerouted the runoff into Weaver's Row?"

    evelyn_hart "We prioritized the main thoroughfares. There were trade-offs—"

    maya_soler "Trade-offs drown people, Evelyn. Trade-offs don't keep an eye on a child's room as water rises."
    "Her response is a look that cannot be pinned. There is a flicker—some small, human thing—but it is swallowed by the storm. You want to name it: guilt, regret, the cost of being right, or the cost of being late. The Schrödinger inside you settles on 'complex.'"

    "Neighbor" "You promised the seawall would keep us safe! We followed what the council said—what was that for if not to save us?"

    "Volunteer" "We run seed by seed—Evelyn's crews build overnight—who's supposed to pay for grief?"
    "The voices collide and no one listens. The argument isn't new; it's just louder now because the stakes are visible and raw. People point and blame, or try to find someone to blame, which is the"
    "oldest human reflex in a place where the sea has taken more than spreadsheets ever could calculate."
    # [Scene: Harbor Entrance & Seawall Construction Zone | Night — Trucks Arrive Too Late]
    hide evelyn_hart
    hide maya_soler

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_4 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Low brass, then collapsing dissonance]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Engines coughing, metal grinding, the distant siren of rescue boats]
    "Evelyn's convoy pulls in with a bureaucratic dignity that feels obscene against grieving hands. The heavy trucks can't do what the tide has already done. They illuminate the town, making damage bone-white and detailed. Workers jump"
    "down, shouting into walkie-talkies; a bulldozer's blade is a useless, shining tooth when the water is already where it is not supposed to be."
    "You can see, in the pool of the floodlight, the shape of a plan that failed because it was not a living thing—because it tried to impose geometry on a living shoreline. You also see the"
    "other plan you helped seed: seedlings torn, oyster cages smashed. The collapse isn't a single failure; it's the multiplication of compromises and urgencies, the way time amplifies small errors into catastrophe."
    "Arin returns to you with a net that hangs like a ragged flag. He moves slowly, face drawn."
    show arin_kai at left:
        zoom 0.7

    arin_kai "We pulled three cages. One of them— (he stops) —it was lined with babies, Maya."
    show maya_soler at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_soler "How many—"

    arin_kai "Not enough. Sam's boy—he was in the boat this afternoon. His hands were small on the lines.' (his jaw tightens) 'We couldn't—"
    "You close your eyes against a smell of diesel and mud and something sweet—little oyster flesh—gone wrong. The world becomes sound: the sob from under the tarp, the sharp edgelike bark of a neighbor cursing, the"
    "repeated mechanical voice of an emergency broadcast telling people to seek high ground. Your insides feel like a torn net."

    "Volunteer" "If we'd had more hands last week, maybe we could've—"
    show lina_park at center:
        zoom 0.7

    lina_park "If we'd had different resources, we might have—"
    hide arin_kai
    show rita_soler at left:
        zoom 0.7

    rita_soler "We have to bury what we can, first. Then we count. Then we tell the rest."
    "You have never felt the weight of a community on your chest before, but here it is: a physical compression, the sum of everyone's fear and expectation. You think of the meetings, the certificates, the pilot"
    "approvals; you think of Calder's conditional terms that sat like a line drawn in wet mud. Your chest tightens until the world is a pinpoint."

    menu:
        "Run to the flooded neighborhood to help evacuate":
            "You sprint through ankle-deep water toward the row of lights that is Weaver's Row. Doors are open, sofas half-submerged; a child clings to a stuffed seal in a living room turned shallow sea. You arm someone with clean towels and lift an old woman over the threshold, your boots sucking in the mud like a held breath."
        "Stay at the flats to organize salvage and preservation of samples":
            "You stay among the seedlings and cages, bark orders through soaked teeth, prioritize what can still be saved. You wrap a broken core in plastic, whispering to it like a promise. People follow; your voice becomes an axis in the chaos."

    # --- merge ---
    "There is no clear right. There is only triage and the terrible arithmetic of loss."
    # [Scene: Pier — Climax of the Storm]
    hide maya_soler
    hide lina_park
    hide rita_soler

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_5 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A single, massive drum roll; strings in full dissonance]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A roar that is not wind or water but both; the snap of the last standing post]
    "The wave comes like a verdict. It doesn't know your name; it knows the contours of the bay and claims them utterly. It hits with a force that is more than physical—time itself seems to lurch."
    "You hang on to a cleat as water sweeps across the pier, sweeping hands, nets, a stack of beloved gloves into a brown, bitter tide."
    "Arin's grip slips. For a second you are both suspended in motion: muscle, weather, failing purchase. He hauls himself out by reflex and by cruelty. The net he holds is shredded; the last oyster cages go"
    "under. Someone screams. Someone sobs. You feel your own voice, small and raw, call something that sounds like prayer, like protest."
    "You think, in an abstract corner of your mind, of the models you trusted—curves, projections, risk matrices. They are paper in the rain. You think of Rita's stories, of how the old shoreline used to breathe,"
    "and how small human hands might have changed that breathing without ever stopping it. You feel the bloom of guilt—a rose opening in frozen soil: hot, sharp, unstoppable. It says you should have foreseen more. It"
    "says you should have moved faster. It says you carry the sum of other people's losses on your shoulders and you are suddenly very small."
    "Evelyn stands on the seawall platform, coat plastered to her, the trucks behind her like witnesses. Her face is a map of choices that led here. For a dizzy instant the two of you are an"
    "island of recognition amid the wreckage: you, who preached small, adaptive labor; her, who promised big, engineered certainty. Neither promise saved the night."
    show evelyn_hart at left:
        zoom 0.7

    evelyn_hart "We did what we could! We called in crews—"
    show maya_soler at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_soler "You delayed. Your 'we' came with machines weighing down the road while people's basements filled. Your 'we' became an afterthought."

    evelyn_hart "Those are hard decisions—"

    maya_soler "Hard decisions became homes under water."
    "For a heartbeat there is a charge between you that is almost physical. Then a child cries, and the charge dissipates into a thousand smaller, more ordinary needs—the towel handed across a knee, the empty bucket"
    "you fill and set aside, the old woman who needs to be carried to a dry van. Anger is an open wound that must be dressed before it turns septic."
    # [Scene: Aftermath — Dawn Breaking, Rubble and Quiet]
    hide evelyn_hart
    hide maya_soler

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_6 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Low, aching cello; a single piano note repeating like a pulse]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Distant engines, murmured counting, the drip of water from everything]
    "The storm relents as dawn goes gray and thin. Exhausted hands move with the practiced stiffness of those who have clambered out of nightmares. People count their losses the way they count fingers—methodically, as if list-making can reassemble what the tide took."
    "You walk the ruined edges of the marsh with Rita at your side. She has a wet shawl and a face like carved wood; she walks slowly, each step deliberate."
    show rita_soler at left:
        zoom 0.7

    rita_soler "We bury what we can. We mark what we cannot yet fix. We tell the children what we remember and then we teach them how to build different."
    show maya_soler at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_soler "I thought— (the sentence unravels) —I thought our hands could be enough. I thought the town could grow the future without trading it away. I thought—"

    rita_soler "You thought with a heart, child. That is how we start. But the sea will teach us how to think with this, too. We learn from what it takes."
    "You want to argue, to insist that someone pay for faulty promises, to find a ledger to hold accountable. Instead you let the sorrow sit, let it make a dent in you like a tide shaping"
    "a shoreline. There's work ahead, and there will be talks and hearings and angry letters. There will also be funerals for small things—lost seedlings, drowned cages, a weekend's wages that won't be paid."
    "Arin finds you and takes your hand without looking. His fingers are cracked and bleeding at the knuckles; he does not need to say anything. You stand for a long time looking at the bay that"
    "used to cradle your childhood and now holds the shape of what has been taken. You feel the community's grief like a second skin."
    show arin_kai at center:
        zoom 0.7

    arin_kai "We'll make it right—"
    "Maya Soler: (you let the words out and they are not a lie) 'We'll try.'"
    "He squeezes your hand. Neither of you pretends the attempt can undo what happened. But attempt is a vow. And vows, in their smallness, are the only things left that feel solid."
    "You walk back toward the town with a list forming in your head—not policy points but names, the people you must visit, the seedlings to replant, the places to document. The fight will not be over"
    "because the storm took a lot; grief does not permit tidy endings. But in the wet hush you make a promise to the bay and to yourself: you will do the counting, you will bear witness,"
    "you will tell the story honest and unsoftened."
    "There is no triumph. There is naming. There is the stubborn, terrible work of rebuilding."
    hide rita_soler
    hide maya_soler
    hide arin_kai

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_7 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A low chord resolves slowly into silence]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A gull cries once; somewhere a child laughs—a small, defiant sound]
    "You fold your hands around a cup of coffee someone offers; it is scalding and real. You lift it and for the first time since the storm your breath evens. The town is a long list"
    "of things to repair and a longer ledger of things gone. Your role is no longer only scientist and advocate; tonight you carried people and harvests and blame. You are tired, and sorrow makes you honest."
    "You will speak at the meeting to come; you will fight at the council table; you will help stack sandbags and catalog broken cores. You do not know whether the coming months will favor compromise or"
    "recrimination. You do not know whether your relationship with Arin will survive the strain of this season. You do know this: the bay remembers and names those it takes, and you remember, too."
    # [Scene: Rooftop Terrace | Morning — First Light]

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_8 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Sparse piano; one held voice]
    "You look over Lira Bay in the clean, cold light and see the town awake and raw. People move like soft machinery—functional and broken. You feel a grief that is not a single thing but a"
    "landscape: erosion and cliffs, marsh and seawall, people torn and people holding. It is very negative, a truth you cannot soften, and it is heavy. Your arousal has fallen from the panic of the storm but"
    "remains electric—an alive, sharp feeling of responsibility and resolve."
    show rita_soler at left:
        zoom 0.7

    rita_soler "We give names. We mark. We rebuild with memory."
    "You nod. You tuck that into your chest like a small stone—something to throw later at meetings, at the indifferent, at the easy promises. For now you keep it as ballast. The ending is not a happy unraveling or a tidy reconciliation; it is heavy and necessary."
    "You turn and speak, not to anyone in particular, making a vow that is more action than posture."
    show maya_soler at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_soler "We'll document. We'll grieve. We'll fight with facts and stubbornness. We will show what the bay needed."
    show arin_kai at center:
        zoom 0.7

    arin_kai "And you'll have people—if you'll let us."
    "Your throat closes. You think of all the times you refused help, of the stubbornness that protected you and isolated you in equal measure. You think of the way his hands have worked tonight—raw, unvarnished labor—and"
    "of the quiet steadiness beneath his anger. You do not know what the next season brings for love, only that shared work may be its own kind of shelter."
    "You look out at the bay one last time. The tide is low now, revealing the scars. The horizon is a raw edge where sky meets water—a place of loss and also, terribly, possibility."
    hide rita_soler
    hide maya_soler
    hide arin_kai

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_9 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Piano fades to a single note, held then released]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The distant murmur of people cataloguing, counting, naming]

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_10 at full_bg
    "THE END"
    # [GAME END]
    return
